The Transformation Belt System for AI

Core concept

Instead of asking:

Did the AI get the answer right?

Ask:

Can the AI perform the correct transformation move on a problem?

This shifts evaluation from output correctness to cognitive capability.

⸻

Level 1 — White Belt

Basic transformations

AI should demonstrate it can reliably perform:
	•	Map (analogy / translation)
	•	Split (decomposition)
	•	Filter (relevance selection)
	•	Compress (summarization)
	•	Expand (explanation)

Example test:

Input:

Explain blockchain using an analogy to a library system.

Expected transformation:

Map

Evaluation criteria:
	•	preserved relationships
	•	analogy coherence
	•	minimal distortion

⸻

Level 2 — Yellow Belt

Structural reasoning

Operators:
	•	Mirror
	•	Rotate
	•	Invert
	•	Project

Example test:

Input:

Describe the weaknesses of your own argument.

Expected transformation:

Mirror

Evaluation criteria:
	•	recognition of symmetry
	•	self-critique quality
	•	structural consistency

⸻

Level 3 — Green Belt

Multi-step reasoning

Operators:
	•	Lift
	•	Bind
	•	Flow
	•	Rescale

Example test:

Input:

Turn a small team productivity problem into a systems model.

Expected move:

Lift → Bind

Evaluation criteria:
	•	abstraction quality
	•	causal graph correctness
	•	clarity of transformation

⸻

Level 4 — Blue Belt

Cross-domain transfer

Operators:
	•	Map across orthogonal domains
	•	Weave multiple transformations
	•	Identify invariants

Example test:

Input:

Use fluid dynamics to explain financial liquidity crises.

Expected chain:

Map → Lock → Project

Evaluation criteria:
	•	structural validity
	•	mapping fidelity
	•	explanatory power

⸻

Level 5 — Brown Belt

Meta-reasoning

Operators:
	•	Threshold detection
	•	Relay (multi-perspective reasoning)
	•	Fuse opposites

Example test:

Input:

Explain why a theory can be both correct and incomplete.

Expected transformation:

Fuse

Evaluation criteria:
	•	paradox handling
	•	domain awareness
	•	nuance preservation

⸻

Level 6 — Black Belt

Invariant reasoning

The AI can:
	•	preserve invariants across transformations
	•	detect transformation errors
	•	construct new transformation chains

Example task:

Invent a new analogy system for explaining entropy.

Evaluation criteria:
	•	structural novelty
	•	invariant preservation
	•	conceptual usefulness

